                <head>51. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On September 27, 1977, Soviet Foreign Minister Andrei <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> returned to Washington from New York,
                    where he was attending the United Nations General Assembly meeting, for an
                    evening meeting with President Jimmy <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName> and Secretary of State Cyrus <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                        >Vance</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> presented
                    Soviet responses to the earlier <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss>
                    discussions with the United States, addressing specifically the earlier
                    negotiations pertaining to <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>ed missiles.
                    The memorandum of conversation is printed as <ref target="frus1969-76v33#d184"
                        >Document 184 in <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, volume
                        XXXIII, <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> II, 1972–1980</ref>.</p>
            </div>
